# Authentication, RBAC & Input Security

Source: GENERAL_CLAUDE.md §§ Authentication & Security, RBAC, Input Security, Rate Limiting.

NON-NEGOTIABLE when project includes authentication or you are implementing auth.

## Authentication invariants

- **Access token:** asymmetric signing (RS256/ES256), max 15m, memory-only in SPAs, Bearer header.
- **Refresh token:** HTTP-only Secure SameSite=Strict cookie, rotation + family tracking, server-side blocklist.
- **Passwords:** adaptive hash (bcrypt/argon2/scrypt), ≥bcrypt-12 equivalent, min 12 chars, complexity, breach check.
- **MFA:** TOTP or WebAuthn; secrets encrypted at rest; 10 hashed backup codes.
- **Sessions:** bind to user-agent/IP, concurrent limits, force-logout, audit trail.

Use the stack's established auth libraries.

## RBAC

Roles: `admin` → inherits `user` → inherits `viewer`.

- Roles in token/session AND verified server-side every request.
- Auth middleware/guard before authorization always.
- Ownership checks separate from role checks.
- Audit log privilege escalation attempts.

## Input security

- Validate ALL boundaries with schema library (Zod, Pydantic, Joi, etc.).
- Sanitize HTML output; parameterized queries via ORM; raw SQL needs review comment.
- Validate uploads server-side; strip unknown request fields.

## Rate limiting (HTTP APIs)

| Tier | Window | Max |
|------|--------|-----|
| auth_endpoints | 15m | 10 |
| api_general | 1m | 100 |
| api_authenticated | 1m | 300 |

Persistent store in production. Progressive delays and IP blocking after violations.
